300 428 1755 (secure electronic mail messages.  In order for the RIPEM system to be valid, it must insure that only the) 1755 SB
300 478 1764 (intended recipient of a message can read the message.  It must also protect against willful changes to the) 1764 SB
300 528 1721 (message and transmission errors.  It also should insure that the message comes from the person that it) 1721 SB
300 578 202 (says it does.) 202 SB
450 628 1625 (The message itself is encrypted with the U.S. Data Encryption Standard cipher \(DES\).  This is a) 1625 SB
300 678 1800 (conventional cipher that uses a 56 bit key.  The DES algorithm is used to encrypt the message because it is) 1800 SB
300 728 1708 (much faster than a public key encryption system.  The DES key is generated randomly by the RIPEM) 1708 SB
300 778 1799 (program.  No two identical DES keys are ever generated.  The DES key is then encrypted by RIPEM using) 1799 SB
300 828 1732 (the RSA public key encryption system.  The sending RIPEM program uses the recipient's public key to) 1732 SB
300 878 1747 (encrypt the DES key.  RIPEM obtains this key from the RIPEM key server program.  Only the intended) 1747 SB
300 928 1746 (recipient will be able to decipher the DES key with their secret key.  If there is more than one recipient,) 1746 SB
300 978 1080 (the DES key must be encrypted with each recipient's public key.) 1080 SB
450 1028 1481 (A cryptographically secure hash function is also used to protect the message.  The MD5) 1481 SB
300 1078 1758 (algorithm is used to create a hash value, or checksum, of the plaintext message.  This hash function will) 1758 SB
300 1128 1780 (detect any changes made to the original text.  The sending RIPEM program encrypts this hash value with) 1780 SB
300 1178 1655 (the sender's private key.  The DES encrypted plaintext, the RSA encrypted DES key, and the RSA) 1655 SB
300 1228 1394 (encrypted MD5 hash result is then sent to the recipient via normal electronic mail.) 1394 SB
450 1278 1628 (When the recipient receives a RIPEM message, they first must use their secret key to decrypt the) 1628 SB
300 1328 1798 (DES encryption key.  The DES key is then used to decipher the message.  RIPEM then computes the MD5) 1798 SB
300 1378 1759 (hash value for this message.  It also deciphers the MD5 hash function result with the sender's public key) 1759 SB
